{[%evp 0,27,27,16,39,32,18,-12,73,73,73,25,72,98,104,85,95,61,110,108,109,86,
87,79,76,56,74,55,55,55]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 {In this chapter, the 3rd
move sidelines will be analyzed. They are very rare, but it's still good to
know how to play against them.} Bb4 {Is a suspicious move since it allows the
bishop to get hit with c3 with tempo, which is a typical move that White wants
to play anyway. 3...Bb4 was played by Magnus Carlsen and some other strong
players in blitz games, so it should be analyzed.} (3... Qf6 {Black's idea is
to prevent d4 and to follow-up with moves like Bc5, Nge7 and Ng6.} 4. c3 {
A typical move in the Spanish opening. White wants to play d2-d4.} (4. Nc3 $5 {
[%cal Gc3d5] Is also good, since Nd5 comes with tempo.} Nge7 (4... a6 5. Nd5
Qd8 6. Ba4 Nf6 7. c3 $16 {[%cal Gd2d4] If Black exchanges on d5, after exd5
forces the knight to move from c6, the pawn on e5 will be hanging.}) 5. O-O {
With the idea of playing Re1, Nd5, and even d2-d4 in some cases, opening up
the position.}) 4... g5 {Black wants to play g4.} (4... Bc5 $6 {Black is
trying to prevent d4, however, it's an unsuccessful attempt.} 5. d4 exd4 6. e5
{Capturing the pawn on e5 with Nxe5 would run into Qe2, pinning the knight.}
Qg6 7. cxd4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 {Black can't really capture on g2 due to Rg1.} Nge7 9.
O-O d5 10. Ne2 $18 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Ge2f4] It's interesting that this position
is not just better for White, in fact, it's winning. The queen on g6 is
misplaced and it needs some time to get back to safety with Qf5-Qd7, and in
the meantime, Nf4 is White's idea.}) (4... Nge7 5. d4 $16 {[%cal Gc1g5]}) (4...
a6 5. Ba4 d6 6. d4 Bd7 {This position resembles the Steinitz variation,
although here the queen is on f6 which is very strange.} 7. O-O {[%csl Rf6]
Black needs to be careful as the move Bg5 can cause problems.} h6 8. Be3 {
[%cal Gb1d2]} Nge7 {This is too slow for Black, and now White has many moves
and plans to choose from.} 9. d5 {A direct solution.} (9. Nbd2 $16) (9. c4 $5 {
[%cal Gb1c3] With the idea to develop with Nc3 and play Nd5 at some point.})
9... Nb8 10. Qb3 b6 ({The point is that after:} 10... b5 $2 11. c4 $18 {
[%csl Ra8][%cal Gb3b7] and capturing bxa4 would lead to losing the rook in the
corner.}) 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. a4 $16 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gc3c4] With the idea to push
a4-a5 and c4 next. If Black pushes a6-a5 instead, White has the idea to play
Na3, Qc4, and Nb5, in order to attack the c7-pawn. In any case, Black needs a
lot of time in order to develop the kingside.}) 5. d4 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gc1g5]}
g4 (5... h6 6. Be3 $16) 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5 Qxe5 8. Bd3 {Black's pieces are
undeveloped and it will take some time to get them in the game.} Nf6 (8... d5
9. Be3 $16 {[%cal Ge3d4]}) 9. O-O Bd6 10. g3 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Qh5 11. Be3 O-O 12.
Nd2 Be5 (12... Bc5 13. Nc4 $16 {With the idea to recapture on e3 with the
knight.}) 13. h4 {Blocking the view of the queen on h5.} d6 (13... gxh3 14.
Qxh5 {The endgame is terrible for Black.} Nxh5 15. Be2 Ng7 16. f4 Bf6 17. g4
$16 {White has a big space advantage and e5 or g5 is coming next, while the
pawn on h3 is not going anywhere and can be easily captured later.}) (13... d5
14. Re1 $16 {Black's position is worse because the king on g8 is weak.}) 14.
Nc4 Be6 15. Nxe5 dxe5 16. Qe2 $16 {The bishop pair, the weak king on g8, and
the Black queen stuck on the kingside on the h5-square, are all factors which
make the position very favorable for White.}) (3... Qe7 {Is another rare move
that is objectively not very good for Black. The idea is to protect the
e5-pawn but it looks a bit artificial.} 4. O-O (4. Nc3 $5 {With the idea Nd5.}
Nf6 5. O-O {Leads to a good position for White, although probably simpler is
to play 4.0-0 first, and then to decide how to continue.}) 4... Nf6 (4... Nd8
5. d4 {As Black goes backward, White goes forward!} c6 6. Ba4 d6 7. c4 $16 {
[%cal Gb1c3] The knight comes to c3 next and White's pieces are
better-developed.}) 5. Re1 {Protecting the pawn on e4.} a6 6. Ba4 d6 7. d4 Bd7
8. Nc3 $16 {This is a better version for White of the Steinitz variation, with
either Nd5 or Bg5 coming next.}) (3... Bd6 4. O-O (4. c3 {Is also possible,
but since Black has} f5 {4.0-0 is simpler and better.}) 4... Nge7 (4... Nf6 $2
5. d4 {With the idea if Black captures on d4, White can play e4-e5, forking
Black's pieces.} Qe7 6. Re1 {[%csl Rd6,Re5]} O-O 7. c3 $18 {[%cal Gb1d2] With
Nd2 and Nc4 coming next. Black's pieces are very artificially-placed.}) (4...
Nd4 5. Nxd4 exd4 {This is a better version for White from the Breyer variation,
which will be discussed later.} 6. e5 $16 {[%cal Gd1g4]}) 5. c3 Ng6 6. d4 O-O
7. Be3 a6 8. Be2 $16 {[%cal Gb1d2] White is playing a typical Spanish where
the bishop on d6 is misplaced. Nd2 is coming next, and eventually White can
also play Re1 and g3.}) 4. c3 Ba5 5. Qa4 $5 {A very direct move which is
suggested by the computers.} (5. O-O {This is usually what White plays
automatically.} Nge7 6. d4 $6 exd4 7. cxd4 d5 $11 {And here is Black's idea
which makes the position playable, if the White player is unaware of this
variation. The bishop on a5 is not bad and can go to b6 at some point.}) (5.
Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c4] Is also possible, with the idea Nc4.}) 5... Bb6 (5... Nge7
6. Nxe5 $1 Nxe5 7. Qxa5 N7c6 {Black has some temporary initiative, although
White can easily parry all the threats.} 8. Qa4 Qg5 9. Kf1 {Protecting the
g2-pawn.} a6 10. Be2 Ng6 11. g3 $16 {Preventing Nf4. White's idea is to push
d4, and in order to do that, the bishop on c1 needs to be defended. So White
can either play Na3 or bring back the queen on c2 or d1 in order to defend the
bishop.}) 6. d4 {This is a better version for White from the 5.0-0 variation
shown above, since exd4 and d7-d5 are not possible.} Nf6 {The only way for
Black to put up some resistance in the 3... Bb4 line. The idea of this move
can be seen after 7.dxe5.} (6... Nge7 7. d5 Nb8 8. Nxe5 {White simply won a
pawn.} O-O 9. d6 {Even in this case, d6 is the best move, creating weaknesses
and posing some problems for Black.} cxd6 10. Nc4 $16) (6... exd4 7. cxd4 Nge7
8. d5 Nb8 9. O-O {Black doesn't have enough time to play d7-d6.} O-O 10. d6 $1
cxd6 11. Bf4 {The position looks very good for White already.} d5 12. Bd6 {
[%csl Gd6] This bishop is extremely unpleasant for Black.} Bc7 13. e5 Bxd6 14.
exd6 Nf5 15. Qf4 Qf6 16. Nc3 Nxd6 17. Qxf6 gxf6 18. Bd3 $16 {[%csl Rd5,Rf6]
Capturing on d5 is also good, although 18.Bd3 is simpler. Black has a lot of
weaknesses and White will capture on d5 next. In addition, the knight from f3
will land on the d4-outpost at some point.} (18. Nxd5 $5 Nxb5 19. a4 {With the
idea to play Nc7 next.})) 7. O-O {White wants to capture on e5 now, so Black
has to react in the center.} (7. dxe5 Ng4 {This leads to a complicated
position.} 8. Bxc6 Nxf2 {Black needs to capture the pawn on f2, as otherwise
if Black captures on c6 instead, White would be able to castle in that case.}
9. Bd5 Nxh1 10. Bg5 f6 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bh4 {The position looks interesting
for White, but objectively it's not clear after:} c6 13. Bb3 d5 $13 {White
also hasn't fully developed yet, while Black wants to develop with Be6 next,
so the position is unclear.}) 7... exd4 (7... Nxe4 8. Re1 f5 {White has
several good moves to choose from in this position.} 9. Qb3 $5 {Preventing
Black from playing 0-0.} (9. Bxc6 dxc6 10. Nxe5 O-O 11. Nd2 $16 {With a nice
positional advantage, as the knight on e5 is strong and the bishop on b6 is
blocked.}) 9... Qf6 10. Nbd2 Nxd2 11. Bxd2 e4 12. Ng5 $1 Ne7 {This is probably
more critical than h6, but in any case, the sacrifice is still very good!} ({
The point is after} 12... h6 {to sacrifice the knight with:} 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14.
Rxe4+ Kd8 15. Rae1 {[%csl Rd8] This looks terrible for Black.} d6 16. Rf4 Qg6 {
There are many ways to continue for White, but the best one is:} 17. Qd1 $1 Bd7
18. h4 $18 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gh4h5,Gd1f3] With h5 and transferring the queen to
the kingside next. Black's king is very weak, the pieces are inactive and the
rooks on a8 and h8 are cut-off, so White already has a winning position.}) 13.
Nxe4 $1 fxe4 14. Rxe4 c6 15. Rae1 cxb5 16. Rxe7+ (16. Qd5 $2 {[%cal Gd2g5]} Bd8
$13 {With this move, Black is still in the game.}) 16... Qxe7 17. Rxe7+ Kxe7 {
This is a position with an interesting material imbalance. White will capture
the pawn on b5 and Black's king remains exposed.} 18. Bg5+ (18. Qxb5 $16) (18.
Qd5 $16) 18... Ke8 19. Qxb5 Bd8 {The only move for Black since Qe5 was the
threat.} 20. Qe5+ Kf7 21. Bf4 {Keeping the bishop is a good idea in order to
have another piece to coordinate with the queen.} Be7 22. Qd5+ Ke8 23. Be5 Rf8
24. Bxg7 Rf7 25. Bh6 $16 {[%csl Re8] White has already won 3 pawns and Black's
pieces are still lacking coordination. White's plan can be pushing the pawns
on the kingside next with f4-f5 and g4-g5.}) 8. e5 (8. cxd4 $16 {Is also good.}
) 8... Nd5 9. cxd4 {This is simpler than 9.Bg5!?.} (9. Bg5 $5 {Is a good
alternative.} Nce7 10. c4 h6 11. Bd2 $1 {This is the best move according to
the engines.} c6 12. cxd5 cxb5 13. Qxb5 a6 14. Qe2 d6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. Re1 $16
{The pin on the e-file is very unpleasant for Black.}) 9... O-O 10. Nc3 Nce7
11. Nxd5 (11. Bg5 $5 {Is also possible.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Bg5 f6 (12... Qe8 13.
Rae1 $16 {Black is very passive and playing d6 will be difficult.}) 13. exf6
Nxf6 14. Rae1 $16 {[%cal Ga2g8,Gg5d8,Ge1e8] White has control over the e-file,
the pin on the knight on f6 is unpleasant, and maybe White can even use the
a2-g8 diagonal at some point.} *

