20. Qe3 Rh5 21. Nf3 $16 {Black is still in the game somehow, but White has 2
extra pawns and with that, a clear advantage.}) (7... c6 {White has several
good possibilities which will be analyzed, so it can be seen how the game
could develop.} 8. Qe2 $5 {A rare move with the idea to simply play f4 and Nd2.
} (8. Qh5 {There are many games with this move.} Qe7 9. Bg5 Nf6 10. Bxf6 {
Due to the line with 10.Qh4 below, White can choose to give up the bishop
immediately.} (10. Qh4 {May not be very clear after:} h6 11. f4 O-O 12. Bxf6
Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. f5 {[%csl Rc8]} b5 15. Bb3 a5 16. a4 Bb4 {[%csl Gb4]}
17. Rf2 Ba6 18. Nd2 $14 {White is still slightly better as Nf3 is coming,
although Black can probably hold the position.}) 10... Qxf6 11. f4 O-O 12. Nd2
g6 13. Qh6 Qg7 14. Qh4 $14 {It seems like an easy game for White as f5, Nf3,
and Rae1 are all moves and ideas in this position.}) (8. a3 $5 {Controlling
the b4-square and giving the c4-bishop the option to retreat to the safe
a2-square if needed.} Nf6 (8... Ne7 $6 9. f4 d5 10. Ba2 O-O 11. f5 f6 12. Qh5
$16 {[%cal Gb1d2] With Nd2 next and a potential rook transfer on the kingside
with Rf3. The knight on e7 is not doing anything.}) 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 g5 {
Once again, Black needs to play this move as otherwise, f2-f4 will be played
and it will put Black in a very unpleasant position.} 11. Bg3 O-O 12. Nd2 d5
13. Ba2 Bg4 14. f3 Bh5 15. Qe1 Re8 16. Qf2 Bg6 17. Rae1 $14 {White is very
solid in the center and can aim to push f4 later on.}) 8... Ne7 (8... Nf6 $6 9.
e5 $1 {This is one of the ideas behind placing the queen on e2.} Qe7 10. Re1
dxe5 11. Qxe5 Nd5 (11... Qxe5 12. Rxe5+ Be7 13. Bf4 $16 {It's very difficult
for Black to castle.}) 12. Qxe7+ Bxe7 13. Bxd5 cxd5 14. Bf4 Be6 15. Nd2 Rc8 16.
Rac1 O-O 17. Nb3 Bb4 (17... Bf6 18. Be5 $16) 18. Re2 $16 {[%csl Rd4] White
will capture the pawn on d4 soon.}) 9. f4 O-O (9... d5 10. Bb3 {Should
transpose later on.}) 10. Nd2 d5 (10... Kh8 11. g4 $1 {Preventing f7-f5!}) 11.
Bb3 Kh8 12. g4 $1 a5 13. a4 f6 14. f5 $16 {[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] White is still
very solid in the center, Rf3-Rh3 is coming and Black's king can be in trouble
very soon.}) 8. Qh5 $1 O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10. Nd2 $5 {Is a good waiting move, since
the bishop on g5 is immune from capture.} (10. Bh4 {Is also possible, however,
it leads to a position where Black is solid, although it's still better for
White.} Qe8 11. f4 Kh7 12. Nd2 Bd7 13. f5 f6 14. Qxe8 Raxe8 15. Nb3 b5 16. Nxc5
dxc5 17. Bb3 $14) 10... Be6 (10... hxg5 $2 11. Nf3 g6 12. Qh6 $18 {[%cal Gf3g5]
}) 11. Bxe6 (11. f4 {Is also a good possibility.} Bxc4 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 13. Nxc4
$14 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5][%cal Gf4f5,Gf1f3,Gf3h3] White has the better minor piece
and there are attacking possibilities on the kingside.}) 11... fxe6 12. Bxe7
Qxe7 13. g3 $1 {White is preparing f4.} (13. f4 {Can run into problems after:}
Bb4 {[%csl Rd2] Since Nf3 is not possible due to Rxf4.} 14. Nb3 a5 {White can
play a4 and the position is playable, but the bishop on b4 will be strong.})
13... e5 14. a3 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Rc5b4,Ga3b4] Preventing any Bb4 ideas.} Rf6 {
[%cal Ga8f8]} 15. f4 $1 {White is playing a closed position with the
queen+knight which are better than the queen+bishop.} exf4 16. Rxf4 Qe5 (16...
Rxf4 $6 17. gxf4 Rf8 18. Rf1 $16 {White will start an attack against the Black
king on g8, and possible ideas can include f5 and bringing the knight in the
game with the Nf3-Nh4-Ng6 maneuver.}) 17. Qxe5 (17. Qf3 Raf8 {It's also
possible to continue like this, but there is nothing wrong with trading the
queens.}) 17... dxe5 18. Rxf6 gxf6 19. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gf3h4,Gg1g2]
White has control over the light-squares and the better minor piece, so the
endgame is very pleasant for White.} *

