{[%evp 0,25,21,16,40,45,39,22,46,43,36,20,36,23,36,22,30,25,12,19,35,9,25,13,
26,5,28,23]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nge7 4. d4 {In this version without a6
and Ba4 included, when a6 is played, it gives White extra options such as Bxc6
or retreating with Bc4 or Be2.} (4. Nc3 {White can also play this, but the
move Nc3 is my recommendation against the same position with a6 and Ba4
included, however, in this version, 4.d4 is better.}) 4... exd4 {Black needs
to trade on d4, since the alternatives are not good for Black.} (4... d6 $6 5.
d5 a6 6. Be2 Nb8 7. c4 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gc1e3] This is playing some kind of a
King's Indian where White has a few extra tempi.}) (4... a6 $6 5. Bxc6 Nxc6 6.
d5 Na7 7. Nxe5 Qe7 {Black will get the pawn back, but the position will remain
better for White since the knight on a7 is passive.} 8. Nf3 Qxe4+ 9. Be3 Bb4+ (
9... Bc5 10. Nc3 $16) 10. c3 Bc5 11. O-O Bxe3 12. Re1 O-O 13. Rxe3 $16 {
[%csl Ra7] White has a space advantage with the pawn on d5, the knight on a7
is passive, and White has control over the e-file. Overall, it's a very good
position for White.}) 5. Nxd4 Nxd4 {Is rarer in comparison to 5...Ng6, but
it's objectively the best move.} (5... Ng6 6. Be3 {White can simply develop.}
Be7 (6... Bb4+ 7. c3 Ba5 8. O-O O-O 9. f4 {This position looks like a very
good version for White in comparison to a Scotch game.} Bb6 10. Nc2 $1 {
I prefer this move because it's simpler than 10.f5.} (10. f5 Nge5 11. Qh5 {
Is also possible.} (11. f6 {Leads to a double-edged position after:} gxf6 12.
Nd2 Nxd4 13. cxd4 c6 14. Ba4 d5 $13) 11... f6 12. Nd2 d5 13. Ba4 Kh8 14. Kh1
$14 {White has some pressure, although the position is complicated. That's why
White has the choice to play 10.Nc2! instead.}) 10... Nce7 {Preparing the
d6-d5 push.} (10... Bxe3+ $6 11. Nxe3 d6 12. Nd2 $16 {[%cal Gd1h5,Ga1e1]}) 11.
Bxb6 axb6 12. Bc4 $5 {Preventing d5.} (12. Ne3 d5 $1 {Is unclear.} 13. exd5 (
13. f5 Ne5) 13... Nf5 14. Nxf5 Bxf5 15. Qd4 Ne7 16. d6 (16. Bc4 c6 17. d6 Nc8
18. Rd1 b5 19. Bb3 Qb6 20. Qxb6 Nxb6 21. Nd2 Rad8 22. Nf3 Bg4 23. Kf2 Bxf3 24.
Kxf3 Rd7 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gb6c8]}) 16... cxd6 17. Nd2 $14 {This position is
slightly better for White and there's almost no risk.}) 12... d6 (12... d5 $6 {
Going for d5 anyway isn't working for Black.} 13. exd5 Nf5 14. Qf3 Nd6 15. Nd2
$16 {White is simply a pawn up.}) 13. Ne3 Be6 14. Na3 Bxc4 15. Naxc4 b5 16. Nd2
$14 {White has a space advantage and Qh5 with Rf3-Rh3 can be an idea in the
near future.}) 7. Nc3 (7. Nf5 Bf6 {May be possible, although 7.Nc3 is better.})
7... O-O (7... Bf6 $6 8. Nde2 O-O 9. f4 d6 10. O-O $16 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge2g3] Qd2
and Ng3 are White's next moves, and after that White should consider moves
like Rae1 or Nh5.}) 8. Nf5 {White's pieces are well-developed and Black can
hardly find some active plan.} Bb4 (8... Bf6 $6 9. Qd2 d6 10. O-O-O $16 {
White will push the pawns on the kingside next.}) 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 d5 {
This is the best way for Black, although White still has an advantage.} 11.
exd5 Bxf5 12. dxc6 b6 13. Re1 $14 {White has some weaknesses but is also a
pawn-up. In addition, the bishop will be very strong on the d4-square.}) (5...
a6 6. Be2 $1 {This is an extra possibility in this version where a6 and Ba4
haven't been included.} Nxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qe3 $1 {The plans for White are
easy and they are shown as follows:} g6 (8... Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Bd2 $16 {
[%cal Ge1c1] White will castle long and then White will push the pawns on the
kingside with g4-f4-g5.}) (8... Bb4+ 9. Nc3 d6 10. a3 {Black should probably
capture on c3, but that would lead to a position that is clearly in White's
favor, as White will have control over the center and the bishop pair.} Ba5 (
10... Bc5 11. Qg3 {Attacking the g7-pawn.}) 11. Bd2 $16 {With Qg3, 0-0-0 and
f4 at some point.}) 9. Bd2 $1 {An interesting idea, trying to develop the
bishop on the long diagonal without fianchettoing it.} d6 (9... Bg7 $5 10. Bc3
$1 $16) 10. O-O {This looks slightly better than the alternatives, which are
also playable.} (10. Bc3 {Is not that clear because after:} Rg8 11. O-O g5 12.
Nd2 $14 {Black can maybe try to castle queenside after Be6 and Qd7, although
the position is still slightly better for White.}) (10. Nc3 Bg7 11. O-O-O $14 {
White will expand on the kingside with f4, g4 and/or h4 later on.}) 10... Qe7 (
10... Bg7 11. Bc3 {The trade of the dark-squared bishops will weaken Black's
dark squares.}) 11. Bc3 (11. Nc3 $5 Be6 12. Qg3) 11... Rg8 12. a4 $5 {White is
starting to expand on the queenside.} g5 13. b4 g4 14. b5 Ne5 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16.
Nc3 Be6 17. bxa6 bxa6 18. Rab1 $14 {Black has a nice control in the center
with the queen on e5 and bishop on e6, however, Black's king is weak, White
has the open b-file and Rb7 is coming next.}) (5... g6 6. Nxc6 $5 {White can
capture on c6 with the idea to get the d4-square for the queen.} (6. Be3 Bg7 7.
Nc3 {Is also possible.}) 6... Nxc6 (6... bxc6 $6 7. Qd4 $1 {Taking away
Black's castling possibility.} Rg8 8. Ba4 Bg7 9. Qe3 $16 {Black can't castle
and White can follow up with 0-0, Nc3, and perhaps Rd1. White has an easy game.
}) (6... dxc6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. Bc4 {[%csl Rf7]} Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Be3 $16 {
[%csl Rd8,Re6][%cal Ge1e2,Gb1d2] This is a one-sided endgame where Black has a
lot of weaknesses. White will play Ke2, Nd2, and potentially Nc4 will follow.})
7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2] White wants to castle long!} a6 9. Be2 d6 10.
Qd2 Be6 (10... O-O 11. h4 $1 h5 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. O-O-O $16 {Black can quickly
get in trouble as g2-g4 can be a very unpleasant threat, and it can also be
