possible.} d5 8. Nc3 Be6 9. O-O dxe4 10. Qxe4 Nd5 11. Bd2 $14 {White is
slightly better with no risk, however, White can choose to be more ambitious
with 7.Bc4.}) 7... d5 8. Bb3 Qb6 {8...dxe4 wasn't possible due to 9.Bxf7.} (
8... Be6 $6 9. Nc3 {White is pressing in this position.}) 9. Qd1 $1 {A tricky
move that avoids the queen trade.} (9. Qxb6 {The endgame is fine for Black.}
axb6 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Bxd5 cxd5 12. Nc3 Bb4 13. Bd2 O-O 14. Nxd5 Bxd2+ 15.
Kxd2 Rd8 16. c4 Be6 $11) 9... dxe4 (9... Be6 10. O-O O-O-O 11. Nc3 $14) 10. Nc3
Nf5 ({Black can try, but won't be able to keep the pawn:} 10... Bf5 $6 11. O-O
Rd8 12. Qe2 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc3e4]}) 11. O-O Be7 12. Nxe4 O-O 13. c3 $14 {
[%csl Gb3][%cal Gb3g8,Gc1f4] The bishop on b3 is strong and Qh5 or Qf3 can be
a good follow-up.}) 7. Qe3 $1 Be7 (7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 (8. Bd2 {Is also good.}
Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 $14) 8... O-O 9. Bd2 d6 10. O-O-O $16 {With f4 or h4-h5 next.})
8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O {Castling short is simple and best.} (9. Bd2 {This may look
tempting with the idea to go long castle, but Black has the option of playing:}
Nb4 $1 {It's difficult for White to protect the c2-pawn, and if White goes:}
10. O-O-O c6 11. a3 (11. Ba4 a5 $132 {[%cal Gb7b5]}) 11... d5 $13 {The
position becomes sharp and that's what Black wants - to get some counterplay.})
9... Re8 (9... Nb4 10. Qd2 c6 11. Be2 a5 12. a3 {This is a bit better than 12.
Rd1.} (12. Rd1 $14) 12... Na6 13. Qf4 $14 {White will bring the bishop to e3,
rook to d1, and can even play Qg3 later on.}) (9... d6 10. Nd5 Be6 11. Nxe7+
Qxe7 12. Bd2 a6 13. Be2 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Ge2] White is slightly better and has a
very comfortable position. White has the bishop pair and a4 or f4 can be
played next, while the dark-squared bishop will be well-placed on the
c3-square.}) 10. Rd1 {This is a good prophylactic move and it's more accurate
than the alternatives.} (10. Nd5 Bd6 {This is Black's idea.} 11. Bd2 Ne7 12.
Nf4 Be5 13. Bc3 Ng6 14. Bxe5 Rxe5 15. Bc4 c6 16. Rad1 Qe7 {With a reasonable
position for Black.} 17. Bd3 Nxf4 18. Qxf4 d5 19. exd5 Rxd5 $11) (10. f4 d6 11.
Nd5 $14 {Is also possible.}) 10... d6 11. Nd5 Bd7 (11... Bf8 12. Qg3 $14 {
[%cal Gc1g5] White wants to play Bg5 next.}) 12. Bf1 Bf8 13. c4 $14 {White's
dark-squared bishop can be developed on the a1-h8 diagonal with Bd2 and Bc3,
or with b3 and Bb2. After that, the queen can go to g3 later on. White is
