the 9...Qe7 line.}) 12. Qg4 $1 Bxe5 (12... c5 13. Nxc5 $1 Bxe5 14. Qe4 Rb8 15.
Nd3 $16) 13. Re1 d6 14. Qa4 Qf7 15. Ne4 $16 {Threatening Nxe5 and simply to
capture the pawn on c6.}) (9... Qe7 $6 10. Nd3 Bd4 11. e5 $1 {Using the
Black's queen placement on the e-file.} Bxe5 12. Re1 d6 13. Nxe5 dxe5 14. Bf4
Ng4 15. Qd2 $16 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Rc7,Re5] Black has a damaged pawn structure and
White will play Bg3 and h3 eventually.}) 10. Na4 $1 {This move leads to an
advantage for White and is the second most-played move in the position.} (10.
Nd3 Bd4 {This is a very big theoretical position and it's not my
recommendation.}) (10. Nxc6 $6 {Is not good after:} Qe8) 10... Qe8 (10... Bxf2+
$6 11. Rxf2 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Bg5 Rd4 14. Bxf6 Rxa4 15. Bxe5 Rxe4 16. Bxc7
$16 {Black has some chances to survive but it will be very difficult to hold
this endgame since White will control the d and f-files and Black has a lot of
weaknesses.}) (10... Nxe4 $6 11. Nxc6 Qe8 12. Nxc5 Nxc5 13. Nd4 $16 {[%cal
Gf2f3,Ga8h1] White can play f3 later on with the idea to block the long
diagonal.}) (10... Ba6 $6 11. Nxc5 Bxf1 12. Qxf1 dxc5 13. Qc4+ Kh8 14. Be3 {
[%csl Rc5,Rc6]} Qe7 15. f4 $16 {White sacrificed an exchange but has a clear
positional advantage since the knight is very strong on e5 and Black has a lot
of weak pawns.}) (10... Bb6 {This is a slightly worse version for Black in
comparison to the main line with 10...Qe8.} 11. Nxb6 axb6 12. Nxc6 Qe8 13. Nd4
Qxe4 14. f3 $16) 11. Nd3 (11. Nxc5 $6 Qxe5 12. Nd3 Qxe4 $11) 11... Bg4 {
Black aims to get a better version by provoking the move Qe1 before moving the
dark-squared bishop.} (11... Nxe4 {This is a possible way to continue,
although practically speaking, it will be very difficult for Black.} 12. Naxc5
Nxc5 13. Nxc5 dxc5 {[%csl Rc5,Rc6,Rc7]} 14. Be3 {The best move, targeting the
c5-pawn at once.} (14. Re1 Qg6) 14... Qg6 (14... Qe5 15. Re1 {Doesn't change
much.}) 15. f3 $5 {[%cal Gf1f2] With the idea to bring the rook to f2.} (15.
Qe2 {This is a theoretical move and it's still better for White, so it's also
playable.}) 15... Bf5 (15... Ba6 16. Rf2) 16. Bxc5 (16. Rf2 Rad8 17. Qf1 $14)
16... Bxc2 17. Qd4 Rfd8 18. Qf2 $14 {There is a drawing tendency because of
the opposite-colored bishops, but there are many pieces left on the board and
Black can't trade the queens easily. Black's king is slightly weaker, the
pawns on the queenside are targets, and White can double on the e-file or play
Rc1, which is also an option. Overall, Black has a tough fight for a draw
ahead.}) (11... Bb6 $6 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. f3 $16) (11... Bd4 $6 12. c3 Bb6 13.
Nxb6 axb6 14. f3 $16 {1-0 (38) Howell,D (2670) -Salem,A (2603) Caleta 2015})
12. Qe1 Bd4 13. c3 Bb6 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. f3 Be6 {This is the difference with
the queen on e1 and d1 - the queen doesn't control the b3-square. White can't
establish the b3-c4 pawn structure since 16.b3 runs into 16...Bxb3, so White
needs to play 16.a3 which is not ideal as it's weakening the light squares on
the queenside.} 16. a3 Bc4 17. Qd1 Qg6 {This is the best way to prevent b2-b3
because Black's idea is to meet b3 with Bxd3 and d5.} (17... c5 $6 18. b3 {
With c3-c4 next which is good for White.}) (17... Qf7 18. Re1 Nd7 19. Be3 c5
20. Bf2 $16 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gf2g3] 1-0 (85) Morozov,D (2475) -Bissmann,S (2386)
ICCF email 2019}) 18. Re1 ({If} 18. Nf4 {Black has:} Qf7) 18... Rae8 19. Nf4 (
19. Nf2 d5 20. b3 Ba6 21. e5 Nd7 22. f4 Nc5 {1/2-1/2 (42) Schmidt,T (2347)
-Hernandez Molina,D (2372) ICCF email 2014} 23. Re3 Ne6 24. Rg3 Qf5 25. Rf3 h5
$44 {Black has good compensation due to the blockade on the light squares.})
19... Qf7 20. Be3 g5 (20... Bb3 $6 21. Qe2 Nd7 22. Nd3 Qg6 23. Qd2 Bc4 24. Kh1
d5 25. Nf4 Qf7 26. exd5 cxd5 27. Nh3 h6 28. Bf2 $16 {½-½ (37) Beetsma,M 
(2184) -Villeneuve,R (2144) ICCF email 2019 White is better objectively and
Bg3 can be played next.}) 21. Nd3 (21. Nh3 {Also puts some pressure on Black.}
g4 22. fxg4 Qg6 23. Nf2 Nxe4 24. Nxe4 Rxe4 25. h3 Bd5 26. Qd2 Rfe8 $14 {
Even though Black has drawing chances with the opposite-colored bishops, White
has an extra pawn and the king on g1 is safer than its counterpart.}) 21... Qg6
22. Kh1 g4 23. Nf4 Qf7 24. b4 $14 {Black doesn't want to trade on f3 since
that would open up the g-file and the king on g8 will become vulnerable. White
has an idea to continue with a4-a5 next, creating a passed pawn, and if Black
prevents that with 24...b5, White would get the d4-square for the bishop,
since c5 won't be possible for Black anymore. The position may be objectively
defendable, although in a practical game, White is a pawn up and it will be
difficult for Black to defend.} *

