{[%evp 0,31,21,16,16,14,14,14,10,10,16,45,30,34,34,8,-1,11,-3,-18,-15,-10,0,3,
20,26,23,31,47,40,49,39,51,31]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 {The Berlin
defense is one of the most popular and challenging lines in the Spanish
opening. It's a very solid line, although White can pose Black some problems.}
4. d3 {4.0-0 is the most popular move and there is a lot of theory on it.
Instead, 4.d3 is giving more options for White and it's one of the best ways
to play against the Berlin defense. The main options for Black are 4...Bc5 and
4...d6, which will be analyzed later.} Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge7g6] This has been
played by Richard Rapport in recent years. Black wants to play c6 and Ng6.} (
4... Bd6 {The idea is similar to 4...Bc5. The bishop is protecting the e5-pawn
for now, and Black wants to castle next, play Re8, and bring the bishop back
to f8.} 5. Nbd2 {In comparison to 5.c3, White will get the extra option to
play Nc4.} (5. c3 {Is also possible, but I prefer to start with 5.Nbd2.} O-O 6.
O-O Re8 {[%cal Gd6f8,Ga7a6,Gb7b5]}) 5... a6 (5... O-O 6. Nc4 {[%csl Rd6,Re5]
Black doesn't want to give up the bishop, nor the pawn on e5, so the only way
is to give a check on b4.} Bb4+ 7. c3 d5 {White has several ways to get a good
position:} 8. cxb4 {This is the most unpleasant move for Black practically.} (
8. exd5 Nd4 $1 {If 9.Nxd4 exd4 10. cxb4 Qxd5, it leads to a double attack on
the bishop on b5 and pawn on g2.} 9. Ba4 b5 $13 {This position is unclear as
Black has good counterplay.}) (8. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 9. exd5 {Is also a good option
since White will win a pawn eventually and Black won't have enough
compensation.}) 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 (9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxe5 {White won a pawn but
Black gets some counterplay.} cxd3 11. Qxd3 Qe8 12. f4 a5 $14 {[%cal Gc8a6]
White has the better chances, although easier is 9. Bxc4.}) 9... Bg4 {Black
needs to play this move which eliminates the pressure on the e5-pawn. In
addition, after 10.b5, Black can play 10...Nd4 with a complicated position.}
10. Be3 {Preventing any Nd4 ideas.} Nxb4 {Black wants to capture on f3 now and
White won't be able to recapture with the queen.} (10... Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Nxb4 12.
Qd1 {This move protects everything.} Nc6 13. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Gc4,Ge3] White is
only slightly better but it's a very pleasant position with the bishop pair,
castling next and after that, b4 with Qb3 is an idea. The d4-square is not a
big problem for White since after any Nd4, White can castle and play f4.}) 11.
Qb3 Bxf3 12. Qxb4 Bxg2 13. Rg1 Bf3 14. Rg3 Bh5 15. Qxb7 Rb8 16. Qxa7 Rxb2 17.
Bc5 Re8 18. Qa3 {Kicking the rook away from White's territory, as Re2+ Kf1
doesn't achieve anything for Black.} Rb8 19. Qc1 $40 {[%cal Gc1g5] White's
passed a-pawn can be very strong potentially, the queen can be transferred to
g5, and White's king will find shelter on the kingside with Kf1-Kg2.}) 6. Bxc6
(6. Ba4 b5 7. Bb3 O-O {[%cal Gd6c5,Gd7d6] It leads to a standard position, but
White has a better option on move 6.}) 6... dxc6 7. Nc4 {In the upcoming
chapters, more details will be discussed about this structure when the trade
Bxc6 dxc6 occurs. With 7.Nc4, White is attacking the e5-pawn.} Qe7 (7... Bg4 {
Is not ideal for Black because Black's light-squared bishop will be traded.} 8.
h3 Bxf3 {The positions when Black gives up the light-squared bishop are
slightly better for White in general.} 9. Qxf3 {White's minor pieces are
better than their counterparts, and White has plans of pushing a4 or preparing
the f4-push.} Nd7 10. Qg4 {Preventing 0-0 due to Bh6.} Qf6 11. a4 $14 {[%cal
Ge1g1,Gf2f4,Gg2g3] White will castle next and will aim to play g3-f4 or f4
directly.}) (7... Nd7 8. d4 Qe7 {On 8...exd4 9. Qxd4, the g7-pawn and the
bishop on d6 are attacked.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 Re8 11. dxe5 $5 {The idea is to
create the 4 against 3 pawn structure.} (11. c3 a5 12. Bg5 $6 (12. a4 $142 {
This is more accurate than what was played in the game. White has a pleasant
position.}) 12... f6 13. Bh4 Qf7 $11 {1/2-1/2 (47) Vachier Lagrave,M (2758)
-Aronian,L (2797) Beijing 2014}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nfxe5 Bxe5 13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14.
Re3 $1 {A very important idea, transferring the rook to g3, and White should
also consider playing Bd2 and Bc3.} Be6 15. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3]} Rad8 16. Qc1 $14
{[%cal Gd2c3] Black will probably play f6 at some point, and White's ideas
include Rg3, Bc3, or even f4-f5.}) 8. O-O O-O (8... Bg4 9. h3 Bh5 10. Ne3 $14 {
[%csl Rf5][%cal Ge3f5] With the idea Nf5 and potentially g4 if Black castles
kingside.}) 9. Re1 {[%cal Gd3d4] Preparing d4.} b5 (9... c5 10. a4 b6 11. Bg5
h6 12. Bh4 $14 {White managed to provoke h6, and now Ne3-Nf5 is a bit more
difficult to prevent with g6, as Black is creating weaknesses on the kingside.}
) 10. Ne3 c5 (10... Re8 11. a4 {Doesn't change much.}) 11. b3 $14 {[%cal Gf3h4,
Gg2g3,Gc1d2,Gd1f3,Ga2a4] White's plans can be a4 and Bd2, or Nh4 with Qf3, or
even Nh4 with g3 and eventually f4. Usually Black would like to have the
f6-knight on c6 or e6, although in this case, that would require a lot of
tempi. White has a pleasant position.}) 5. O-O (5. d4 {Leads to an unclear
position.} Nxe4 6. dxe5 c6 7. Bd3 Nc5 8. O-O d5 (8... Ng6 $6 9. Bg5 $16) 9.
exd6 Qxd6 $13 {Black is very close to being completely fine.}) (5. Bc4 {
The bishop steps away so c6 doesn't come with tempo, although Black can play
c6 anyway.} c6 6. Nc3 d6 7. O-O h6 8. d4 Qc7 $13 {Black wants to play Ng6 or
even g5 first. White is probably slightly better, but in the games, it has
been shown that Black also has decent chances.}) (5. Nxe5 $2 c6 {[%csl Rb5,Re1,
Re5][%cal Gd8a5] White loses a piece.}) 5... c6 {It's better for Black to
start with this move, asking the bishop to retreat at once.} (5... Ng6 {
Is a slightly worse version for Black.} 6. d4 c6 7. Bd3 $5 {This is the
difference. The bishop can go to d3 instead of the a4-square in the 5...c6
move order.} (7. dxe5 Nxe4 8. Bd3 d5 {Black is more or less fine here.}) 7...
d5 (7... d6 8. c4 $14 {[%cal Gb1c3]}) (7... exd4 8. e5 Nd5 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10.
Qxd4 d6 11. Re1 {Black has some problems with the king still in the center and
the undeveloped pieces.} Be6 12. c4 dxe5 13. Qxe5 Nf6 14. Ng5 Qd6 15. Bf4 Qxe5
16. Bxe5 $14 {The endgame is very unpleasant for Black. The b1-knight will be
developed to c3 or d2 and in addition, White can capture the bishop on e6.}) 8.
exd5 e4 9. Qe2 Be7 (9... cxd5 $6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. Ne5 $16 {Black's center is
not stable as White has the idea to play c4 and Nc3, with the idea to
undermine it, so Black is in trouble.}) 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4 cxd5 12. Qd3 O-O
{Black has some compensation with the bishop pair and the computers may even
hold it, although practically, it looks very pleasant for White.} 13. Re1 Be6
14. Nc3 Rc8 15. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Gc2c3,Ge2f4,Ge2g3] It won't be very easy to
convert the pawn, but White is the one fighting for the win.}) 6. Ba4 (6. Bc4
Ng6 {White's bishop is not on d3 like in the line arising from 5...Ng6.}) 6...
Ng6 7. c3 {It's better to start with this move because it prevents Black's Bc5
plan, since White would have d4 with tempo.} (7. d4 {Is possible but leads to
an unclear position.} Nxe4 8. Qe2 (8. dxe5 d5 $11) 8... d5 9. c4 Qa5 $13 {
With a very sharp game, although Black is probably fine.}) (7. Re1 Bc5 {
[%cal Gd7d6,Ge8g8]}) 7... Be7 (7... d5 {This is one difference between 7.c3
and 7.Re1, Black has this extra possibility, although it leads to a better
position for White.} 8. exd5 Nxd5 9. Re1 Bg4 (9... Bd6 10. d4) 10. h3 Bxf3 11.
Qxf3 $14 {[%csl Ga4,Gc1][%cal Gb1d2,Gd2e4] With a nice version of the Italian
game. White has the bishop pair and will play Nd2 and Ne4 next.}) 8. Re1 O-O 9.
Nbd2 ({White needs to be a bit careful since after:} 9. d4 {Black has:} d5 $1)
9... d6 (9... d5 {Striking in the center makes sense but it's in White's favor.
} 10. exd5 Qxd5 (10... Nxd5 $6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Bd6 13. Re1 {This is a
worse version for Black from the Marshall attack.} Qh4 14. g3 Qh3 15. Ne4 Bc7
16. Ng5 $16) (10... cxd5 $6 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 Bd6 13. Re1 Bg4 14. Qc2 $16
{[%cal Gd2f1] Black doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 11. Bc2
Re8 (11... Bg4 $6 12. d4 {[%csl Re7] Threatening Bxg6 and Rxe7 in case Black
captures exd4.}) 12. Nc4 {[%csl Re5]} Bg4 13. Ne3 Bxf3 14. Nxd5 Bxd1 15. Nxe7+
Rxe7 16. Rxd1 Rd8 17. g3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gc2][%cal Gg1g2] The position is
clearly in White's favor. White will improve the position further with Kg2, h4,
Be3, a4-a5 is an idea, and overall, White will press for a long time.}) (9...
Qc7 10. d4 exd4 (10... d6 11. Bc2 {Transposes to 9...d6.}) (10... d5 $6 11.
Nxe5) 11. cxd4 d5 12. e5 Nd7 (12... Nh5 $6 13. g3 {[%csl Rh5] The knight is
misplaced on h5.}) 13. Bc2 c5 14. h3 $14) (9... a5 {Black is trying to expand
on the queenside.} 10. Bc2 b5 11. d4 d6 12. a4 Bd7 13. Nf1 Qc7 14. Ng3 $14 {
[%cal Gh2h3,Gc1e3,Gd1d2] With a standard Spanish position where will play h3,
Be3, Qd2, and maybe Nf5 later on.}) 10. Bc2 Re8 {The alternatives are similar
to the main line or they can even transpose in it.} (10... Qc7 11. d4 Bd7 12.
Nf1 h6 13. Ng3 $14) (10... h6 11. d4) 11. d4 Bf8 12. h3 {White is simply
preventing Bg4.} Qc7 13. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1g3]} h6 {With the idea to play Be6.} (
13... d5 $5 {Black needs to know a lot here, otherwise Black will be much
worse.} 14. exd5 (14. Nxe5 Nxe4 {This is Black's idea.}) 14... e4 15. d6 $1 {
An important move.} Bxd6 16. Ng5 {[%csl Re4]} Bf5 17. Ne3 $1 (17. g4 {
Capturing the pawn will lead to an unclear position.} Bd7 18. Nxe4 Nxe4 19.
Rxe4 c5 $44 {White's king is weaker and Bc6 will come soon, so Black has good
compensation.}) 17... Bd7 18. Ng4 $1 (18. Nc4 Bf5 {White has nothing better
than a repetition of moves here, so playing Ng4 is better.}) 18... Nxg4 19.
hxg4 $14 {[%csl Re4] The pawn on e4 is hanging and Black should probably play
c6-c5 in order to give up the pawn and play with some compensation, although
it's not enough.}) 14. Ng3 a5 (14... Be6 15. b3 {[%cal Gc3c4]} b5 {Preventing
c4.} 16. Be3 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1,Gg3f5] White will continue with moves like
Qd2, Rad1, and can try to play Nf5 later on.}) 15. Be3 (15. a4 $5 {Is also
possible.}) 15... b5 16. b3 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2] White is slightly better and has
a very comfortable position.} *

